noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nobelprize.org%2Fprizes%2Fphysics%2F1932%2Fheisenberg%2Ffacts%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EWerner%20Heisenberg%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0and%C2%A0%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nobelprize.org%2Fprizes%2Fphysics%2F1939%2Flawrence%2Fbiographical%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EErnest%20Lawrence%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20compliment%20the%20young%20Oppenheimer%20on%20his%20groundbreaking%20work%20on%20molecules.%20As%20a%C2%A0%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fcitations%3Fhl%3Den%26pli%3D1%26user%3Ddf8z7MQAAAAJ%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ephysical%20chemist%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20Oppenheimer's%20work%20on%20molecular%20quantum%20mechanics%20plays%20a%20major%20role%20in%20both%20my%20teaching%20and%20my%20research.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%223346%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22J.%20Robert%20Oppenheimer%20(left)%20speaks%20to%20another%20individual%20(right)%20in%20front%20of%20a%20chalkboard.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F64cd4b4020f1cf0019caf8fd%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%222509%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EOppenheimer%20is%20often%20credited%20for%20bringing%20quantum%20mechanics%20to%20the%20US.%3Cp%3EBettmann%2FGetty%20Images%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3EThe%20Born-Oppenheimer%20approximation%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EIn%201927%2C%20Oppenheimer%20published%20a%20paper%20called%20%26quot%3B%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1142%2F9789812795762_0001%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EOn%20the%20Quantum%20Theory%20of%20Molecules%3C%2Fa%3E%26quot%3B%20with%20his%20research%20adviser%C2%A0%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nobelprize.org%2Fprizes%2Fphysics%2F1954%2Fborn%2Fbiographical%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EMax%20Born%3C%2Fa%3E.%20This%20paper%20outlined%20what%20is%20commonly%20referred%20to%20as%20the%20Born-Oppenheimer%20approximation.%20While%20the%20name%20credits%20both%20Oppenheimer%20and%20his%20adviser%2C%20most%20historians%20recognize%20that%20the%20theory%20is%20mostly%20Oppenheimer's%20work.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20Born-Oppenheimer%20approximation%20offers%20a%20way%20to%20simplify%20the%20complex%20problem%20of%20describing%20molecules%20at%20the%20atomic%20level.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EImagine%20you%20want%20to%20calculate%20the%20optimum%20molecular%20structure%2C%20chemical%20bonding%20patterns%20and%20physical%20properties%20of%20a%20molecule%20using%C2%A0%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.britannica.com%2Fscience%2Fquantum-mechanics-physics%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Equantum%20mechanics%3C%2Fa%3E.%20You%20would%20start%20by%20defining%20the%20position%20and%20motion%20of%20all%20the%20atomic%20nuclei%20and%20electrons%20and%20calculating%20the%20important%20charge%20attractions%20and%20repulsions%20occurring%20between%20these%20particles%20in%20the%C2%A0%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fchem.libretexts.org%2FBookshelves%2FPhysical_and_Theoretical_Chemistry_Textbook_Maps%2FPhysical_Chemistry_(LibreTexts)%2F09%253A_Chemical_Bonding_in_Diatomic_Molecules%2F9.02%253A_The_H_Prototypical_Species%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Emolecule%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ECalculating%20the%20properties%20of%20molecules%20gets%20even%20more%20complicated%20at%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fquantinuum-new-quantum-computer-microsoft-jpmorgan-nvidia-2023-5%5C%22%3Equantum%20level%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20where%20particles%20have%20wavelike%20properties%20and%20scientists%20can't%20pinpoint%20their%20exact%20position.%20Instead%2C%20particles%20like%20electrons%20must%20be%20described%20by%20a%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.britannica.com%2Fscience%2Fwave-function%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ewave%20function%3C%2Fa%3E.%20A%20wave%20function%20describes%20the%20electron's%20probability%20of%20being%20in%20a%20certain%20region%20of%20space.%20Determining%20this%20wave%20function%20and%20the%20corresponding%20energies%20of%20the%20molecule%20is%20what%20is%20known%20as%20solving%20the%C2%A0%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fchem.libretexts.org%2FBookshelves%2FPhysical_and_Theoretical_Chemistry_Textbook_Maps%2FThermodynamics_and_Chemical_Equilibrium_(Ellgen)%2F18%253A_Quantum_Mechanics_and_Molecular_Energy_Levels%2F18.04%253A_The_Schrodinger_Equation_for_a_Molecule%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Emolecular%20Schr%C3%B6dinger%20equation%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EUnfortunately%2C%20this%20equation%C2%A0%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1134%2FS1063779622010038%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ecannot%20be%20solved%20exactly%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0for%20even%20the%C2%A0%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fchem.libretexts.org%2FBookshelves%2FPhysical_and_Theoretical_Chemistry_Textbook_Maps%2FPhysical_Chemistry_(LibreTexts)%2F09%253A_Chemical_Bonding_in_Diatomic_Molecules%2F9.02%253A_The_H_Prototypical_Species%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Esimplest%20possible%20molecule%2C%20H%E2%82%82%E2%81%BA%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20which%20consists%20of%20three%20particles%3A%20two%20hydrogen%20nuclei%20(or%20protons)%20and%20one%20electron.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOppenheimer's%20approach%20provided%20a%20means%20to%20obtain%20an%20approximate%20solution.%20He%20observed%20that%20atomic%20nuclei%20are%20significantly%20heavier%20than%20electrons%2C%20with%20a%20single%20proton%20being%20nearly%202%2C000%20times%20more%20massive%20than%20an%20electron.%20This%20means%20nuclei%20move%20much%20slower%20than%20electrons%2C%20so%20scientists%20can%20think%20of%20them%20as%20stationary%20objects%20while%20solving%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.insider.com%2Fschrodingers-cat-experiment-2016-5%3F_gl%3D1*1uxtdho*_ga*MTY2MTYzODg5NS4xNjg4MDY4MjQy*_ga_E21CV80ZCZ*MTY5MTE3NDcwOC43Ny4xLjE2OTExNzU0NzguMjEuMC4w%5C%22%3ESchr%C3%B6dinger%3C%2Fa%3E%20equation%20solely%20for%20the%20electrons.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThis%20method%20reduces%20the%20complexity%20of%20the%20calculation%20and%20enables%20scientists%20to%C2%A0%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fchem.libretexts.org%2FBookshelves%2FPhysical_and_Theoretical_Chemistry_Textbook_Maps%2FBook%253A_Quantum_States_of_Atoms_and_Molecules_(Zielinksi_et_al)%2F10%253A_Theories_of_Electronic_Molecular_Structure%2F10.01%253A_The_Born-Oppenheimer_Approximation%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Edetermine%20the%20molecule's%20wave%20function%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0with%20relative%20ease.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThis%20approximation%20may%20seem%20like%20a%20minor%20adjustment%2C%20but%20the%20Born-Oppenheimer%20approximation%20goes%20far%20beyond%20just%20simplifying%20quantum%20mechanics%20calculations%20on%20molecules.%20It%20actually%20shapes%20how%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fchemists-whose-discoveries-changed-our-lives-2013-10%5C%22%3Echemists%3C%2Fa%3E%20view%20molecules%20and%20chemical%20reactions.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhen%20scientists%20visualize%20molecules%2C%20we%20usually%20think%20of%20them%20as%20a%20set%20of%20fixed%20nuclei%20with%20shared%20electrons%20that%20move%20between%20nuclei.%20In%20chemistry%20class%2C%20students%20typically%20build%20%26quot%3B%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1021%2Fed048p407%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eball-and-stick%3C%2Fa%3E%26quot%3B%20models%20consisting%20of%20rigid%20nuclei%20(balls)%20sharing%20electrons%20through%20a%20bonding%20framework%20(sticks).%20These%20models%20are%20a%20direct%20consequence%20of%20the%C2%A0%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1007%2Fs002149900049%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EBorn-Oppenheimer%20approximation%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221654%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22adrenaline%20chemical%20molecule%20structure%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F64cd478020f1cf0019caefbe%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221241%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EThe%20ball%20and%20stick%20model%20of%20molecules%20that%20was%20made%20possible%20by%20Oppenheimer's%20work.%20This%20is%20a%20model%20of%20adrenaline.%3Cp%3EJynto%2FPublic%20Domain%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20Born-Oppenheimer%20approximation%20also%20influenced%20how%20scientists%20think%20about%20chemical%20reactions.%20During%20a%20chemical%20reaction%2C%20atomic%20nuclei%20are%20not%20stationary%3B%20they%20rearrange%20and%20move.%20Electron%20interactions%20guide%20the%20nuclei's%20movements%20by%20forming%20an%C2%A0%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fchem.libretexts.org%2FCourses%2FUniversity_of_California_Davis%2FUCD_Chem_107B%253A_Physical_Chemistry_for_Life_Scientists%2FChapters%2F2%253A_Chemical_Kinetics%2F2.06%253A_Potential_Energy_Surfaces%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eenergy%20surface%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20which%20the%20nuclei%20can%20move%20on%20throughout%20the%20reaction.%20In%20this%20way%2C%20electrons%20drive%20the%20molecule's%20progression%20through%20a%20chemical%20reaction.%20Oppenheimer%20demonstrated%20that%20the%20way%20electrons%20behave%20is%20the%20essence%20of%20chemistry%20as%20a%20science.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%22889%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22D-Wave%20quantum%20computer%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F603ec6522dc90100183550a9%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22667%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EThe%20D-Wave%20quantum%20computer.%20The%20field%20of%20quantum%20computing%20wouldn't%20be%20possible%20without%20Oppenheimer's%20work.%3Cp%3ED-Wave%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3EComputational%20quantum%20chemistry%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20the%20century%20since%20the%20publication%20of%20the%20Born-Oppenheimer%20approximation%2C%20scientists%20have%20vastly%20improved%20their%20ability%20to%20calculate%20the%20chemical%20structure%20and%20reactivity%20of%20molecules.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThis%20field%2C%20known%20as%20computational%20quantum%20chemistry%2C%20has%20grown%20exponentially%20with%20the%20widespread%20availability%20of%20faster%2C%20more%20powerful%20high-end%20computational%20resources.%20Currently%2C%20chemists%20use%20computational%20quantum%20chemistry%20for%20various%20applications%20ranging%20from%20discovering%20novel%C2%A0%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1016%2Fj.cplett.2021.138723%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Epharmaceuticals%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0to%20designing%20better%C2%A0%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1039%2FD0TC03709E%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ephotovoltaics%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0before%20ever%20trying%20to%20produce%20them%20in%20the%20lab.%20At%20the%20core%20of%20much%20of%20this%20field%20of%20research%20is%20the%20Born-Oppenheimer%20approximation.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EDespite%20its%20many%20uses%2C%20the%20Born-Oppenheimer%20approximation%C2%A0%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Felliptigon.com%2Fwhen-born-oppenheimer-fails%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eisn't%20perfect%3C%2Fa%3E.%20For%20example%2C%20the%20approximation%20often%20breaks%20down%20in%20light-driven%20chemical%20reactions%2C%20such%20as%20in%20the%20chemical%20reaction%20that%C2%A0%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1038%2Fnchem.894%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eallows%20animals%20to%20see%20light%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Chemists%20are%C2%A0%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1098%2Frsta.2020.0375%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Einvestigating%20workarounds%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0for%20these%20cases.%20Nevertheless%2C%20the%20application%20of%20quantum%20chemistry%20made%20possible%20by%20the%20Born-Oppenheimer%20approximation%20will%20continue%20to%20expand%20and%20improve.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20the%20future%2C%20a%20new%20era%20of%C2%A0%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.scientificamerican.com%2Farticle%2Fhow-quantum-computing-could-remake-chemistry%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Equantum%20computers%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0could%20make%20computational%20quantum%20chemistry%20even%20more%20robust%20by%20performing%20faster%20computations%20on%20increasingly%20large%20molecular%20systems.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%3ERead%20the%20original%20article%20on%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Foppenheimer-quantum-physics-work-overshadowed-by-atom-bomb-2023-8%5C%22%3EBusiness%20Insider%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1691178810000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F64cd3765f5d4870019e1dcf4%3Fformat%3Djpeg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Foppenheimer-quantum-physics-work-overshadowed-by-atom-bomb-2023-8%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22J.%20Robert%20Oppenheimer%20is%20remembered%20as%20the%20father%20of%20the%20atomic%20bomb%2C%20but%20he%20had%20a%20lucrative%20career%20before%20that.%20His%20theories%20are%20still%20in%20use%20today.%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22insider%40insider.com%20(Aaron%20W.%20Harrison)%22%2C%22engagement%22%3A22%2C%22canonicalUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Foppenheimer-quantum-physics-work-overshadowed-by-atom-bomb-2023-8%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22Ron%20DeSantis%20says%20he%20was%20too%20busy%20overseeing%20an%20execution%20in%20Florida%20to%20watch%20the%20Trump%20arraignment%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%222000%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Florida%20Gov.%20Ron%20DeSantis%20at%20the%20Family%20Leadership%20Summit%20on%20July%2014%2C%202023%20in%20Des%20Moines%2C